The Law Society of Kenya has asked the PSC to take action against public officers forcing Kenyans to register as voters.More than 500 Murang&rsquo;a traders were reportedly ejected from Madaraka market in Thika after refusing to get listed in Kamenu ward on February 6.Gatanga subcounty administrator George Gitau said a local politician was behind the &ldquo;unfortunate&rdquo; and &ldquo;undemocratic&rdquo; move."The intimidation of potential voters sets the stage for violations under Article 38(2) by which the citizen must be accorded the right to freely express his or her will as an elector," said LSK chairman Isaac Okero."This is a gross violation of the right of every Kenyan citizen, under Article 38(3)(a) of the Constitution, to be registered as a voter without unreasonable restriction."Read: Murang&rsquo;a traders evicted from market, forced to list as votersIn a statement on Wednesday, Okero said a PSC warning would greatly assist in curbing such tendencies.He said the action by public officers amounted to very serious breach of the general code of conduct and ethics as stated in Public Officers Ethics Act, 2004."Voting and the requirement to be registered is not an obligation under the laws of Kenya," he said.Okero urged the PSC to consider issuing such a warning and the people to report any incidents."This communication shall give assurance to the public that violation of their constitutional rights by the unlawful actions of public officers will not be tolerated," he said.As the February 14 deadline approaches, the IEBC has only managed to list 2.5 million people less. The target is between four and six million.In January, a man was arrested in Kisumu after a voter registration exercise turned chaotic. Residents said youths violently forced them to register, prompting the arrest by Flying Squad police. More on this: One arrested during chaos at Kisumu voter listing centreArticle 38 of the constitution states;1) Every citizen is free to make political choices, which includes the right--(a) to form, or participate in forming, a political party;(b) to participate in the activities of, or recruit members for, a political party; or(c) to campaign for a political party or cause.(2) Every citizen has the right to free, fair and regular elections based on universal suffrage and the free expression of the will of the electors for--(a) any elective public body or office established under this Constitution; or (b) any office of any political party of which the citizen is a member.(3) Every adult citizen has the right, without unreasonable restrictions, --(a) to be registered as a voter;(b) to vote by secret ballot in any election or referendum; and(c) to be a candidate for public office, or office within a political party of which the citizen is a member and, if elected, to hold office.